<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,609]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">
Female (
<typeStatus box="[297,389,151,177]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">allotype</typeStatus>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[458,600,151,178]" name="Afghanistan" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
). Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[776,864,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1688,1712]" captionTargetBox="[154,1420,388,1665]" captionTargetId="figure-125@2.[151,1436,381,1665]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus and male palp of Indozodion lindbergi (Roewer, 1960). A male habitus, dorsal; B female habitus, dorsal; C–F palp, dorsal, retrolateral, prolateral and ventral. Scale bars = 0.2 mm, unless stated otherwise. Abbreviations: Ta—tegular apophysis, Tl—lamellar extension of the tegular apophysis, Va—ventro-retrolateral apophysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683466" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683466/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
. Total length 5.30. Carapace 2.24 long, 1.55 wide. Eye sizes: AME: 0.17, ALE: 0.12, PME: 0.08, PLE: 0.11. Carapace yellowish brown, darker at pars cephalica. Chelicerae light brown. Sternum, labium and maxillae yellowish. Legs yellowish, without annulations; distolateral portion of Fe I and entire Ti I darker. Abdomen dorsally dark grayish and with a pale posterior spot; beige ventrally, margins of book lungs more heavily sclerotized than opercula. Spinnerets uniformly yellowish. Measurements of legs: I: 6.84 (1.74, 0.65, 1.51, 1.85, 1.09), II: 6.70 (1.73, 0.67, 1.30, 1.88, 1.12), III: 7.05 (1.82, 0.71, 1.35, 2.17, 1.00), IV: 9.00 (2.40, 0.75, 2.11, 2.77, 0.97).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,609]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">
Epigyne as in 
<figureCitation box="[364,486,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1925,1949]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1184,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-121@3.[151,1436,1181,1901]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Epigyne and vulva of Indozodion lindbergi (Roewer, 1960). A macerated epigyne, ventral; B vulva, dorsal; C intact epigyne, ventral; D right receptacle, dorsal; E left receptacle, dorsal. Scale bars = 0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Oc—copulatory opening, Re—receptacle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683477" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683477/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Fig. 3A–E</figureCitation>
; almost 2 times wider than long, semicircular, lacking fovea and hood, with poorly distinct, slit-like copulatory openings (
<emphasis box="[573,606,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Oc</emphasis>
) leading directly to receptacles (
<emphasis box="[958,988,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Re</emphasis>
); copulatory ducts indistinct; receptacles oval, slightly longer than wide, separated by more than 4 diameters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,609]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,511,537]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Note.</emphasis>
The conductor is reduced in size in both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zamani &amp; Marusik" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Roewer" baseAuthorityYear="1960" box="[734,860,511,537]" class="Arachnida" family="Zodariidae" genus="Indozodion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lindbergi">
<emphasis box="[734,860,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">I. lindbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ovtchinnikov" authorityYear="2006" box="[917,1076,511,537]" class="Arachnida" family="Zodariidae" genus="Indozodion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inayatullahi">
<emphasis box="[917,1076,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">I. inayatullahi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and apparently it is the tegular apophysis that functions as a conductor in these two species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1344,582,609]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,150,609]" box="[199,1344,582,609]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,582,608]" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known from one locality in northern 
<collectingCountry box="[779,874,583,609]" name="Pakistan" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
and two localities in eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1199,1340,583,609]" name="Afghanistan" pageId="4" pageNumber="427">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
